                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 16. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>One <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> <choice><orig>hath</orig> wings, the other none.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 16.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>The <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> prince of beasts in might and sway</l>
                        <l>Fights without fear, and <choice><orig>scornes</orig><reg>scorns</reg></choice> to <choice><orig>runne</orig> away:</l>
                        <l>Give him a Spouse with wings of his <choice><orig>owne</orig> race,</l>
                        <l>To mount him with <choice><orig>herselfe</orig> from place to place;</l>
                        <l>But <choice><orig>hee</orig> immoved stands, and nulls her force,</l>
                        <l>By <choice><orig>Embleme</orig> to demonstrate Natures course.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="54"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 16.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>It is a thing <choice><orig>knowne</orig> by experience that a <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> <choice><orig>excells</orig> other <choice><orig>animalls</orig> not<milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/><orig>soe</orig> much in <choice><orig>bignesse</orig> and strength of body, as generosity: if <choice><orig>hee</orig> be seen in<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>hunting, being <choice><orig>ashamd</orig><reg>ashamed</reg></choice> to <choice><orig>runne</orig> away, <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>releaseth</orig><reg>releases</reg></choice> <choice><orig>himselfe</orig> by degrees,
                        <lb/>if <choice><orig>hee</orig> be <choice><orig>oppressd</orig> by a multitude: being removed from the view of the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>hunters, <choice><orig>hee</orig> makes hast away, thinking it a <choice><orig>dishonour</orig><reg>dishonor</reg></choice> to be <choice><orig>excusd</orig><reg>excused</reg></choice> by ab
                        <lb break="no"/>sconding: <choice><orig>hee</orig> desires a wood in flight, which <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>useth</orig><reg>uses</reg></choice>, when anything
                        <lb/>pursues: his bones are solid and not at all empty, which are <choice><orig>sayd</orig> to be
                        <lb/><orig>soe</orig> hard, that being <choice><orig>shakd</orig><reg>shaked</reg></choice> together they <choice><orig>yeild</orig> fire as out of a Steel and<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>flint. <choice><orig>Hee</orig> fears fire above all things. <choice><orig>Hee</orig> seems to derive his substance
                        <lb/>from the nature of the <choice><orig>Sunne</orig>, for in force and heat <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>excells</orig> other<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>animalls</orig>, as the <choice><orig>Sunne</orig> <choice><orig>doth</orig> the <choice><orig>Starrs</orig>: Besides <choice><orig>hee</orig> is <choice><orig>allways</orig> beheld with
                        <lb/>fiery and open eyes, as the <choice><orig>Sunne</orig> beholds the earth with an open and<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>fiery eye: a <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig><reg>Lioness</reg></choice> fighting for her whelps <choice><orig>fixeth</orig><reg>fixes</reg></choice> her eyes upon the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>ground, that <choice><orig>Shee</orig> may not be <choice><orig>afrayd</orig> of the hunters Staffs and Spears.<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>where a <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> perceives the coition of a Leopard, <choice><orig>hee</orig> takes revenge<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>upon the <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> for adultery, and inflicts severe punnishment;<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>The <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> therefore <choice><orig>washeth</orig><reg>washes</reg></choice> away the <choice><orig>offence</orig><reg>offense</reg></choice> and scent in a river,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>or being conscious of the <choice><orig>trespasse</orig><reg>trespass</reg></choice> <choice><orig>doth</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> accompany the adulterer<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>flying for fear of the make: Which <choice><orig>wonderfull</orig> nature of this beast the
                        <lb/>Philosophers contemplating, have produced <choice><orig>severall</orig> <choice><orig>allegoryes</orig> of the
                        <lb/><orig>Lyon</orig>, as it were <choice><orig>hieroglyphicall</orig> writings testifying of their secret<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>worke</orig>, observing the <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> to be a constant, <choice><orig>firme</orig> <choice><orig>animall</orig>, without<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><choice><orig>deceipt</orig><reg>deceit</reg></choice> and suspicion, they assimilated the better part of their <choice><orig>Phi
                        <lb break="no"/>losophicall</orig> composition to him: for as <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>flyes</orig> not, <choice><orig>soe</orig> neither this:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>hee</orig> with solid bones, <choice><orig>soe</orig> this fixed and not to be overcome: and as<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> is not <choice><orig>allways</orig> innocent and free from adultery, <choice><orig>soe</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>is neither Luna nor Mercury without some blemish, but is <choice><orig>joyned</orig>
                        <lb/>by the ignorant sometimes to this, sometimes to that matter, where
                        <lb break="no"/>by an adulterous conjunction of things discrepant and different in
                        <lb/>nature rather than true matrimony is established: for the products
                        <lb/>of a Leopard and <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> have <choice><orig>noe</orig> specious and comely mains<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>about the <choice><orig>necke</orig> and Shoulders; with which <choice><orig>ensigne</orig><reg>ensign</reg></choice> those generated
                        <lb/>by the <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> are alone adorned. The <choice><orig>Philosophicall</orig> <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> must
                        <lb/>therefore be <choice><orig>joyned</orig> to her proper mate or male, and a genuine<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and generous whelp will from <choice><orig>theme</orig> Spring, which may easily
                        <lb/>be <choice><orig>knowne</orig> by his paw. But the <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> must not be any or<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>what you pledge, but winged, which may be able to fight and
                        <lb/>contest with the <choice><orig>Lyon</orig>, depending upon the <choice><orig>Swiftnesse</orig><reg>Swiftness</reg></choice> of her<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>plumes, lest (to <choice><orig>witt</orig>) <choice><orig>Shee</orig> Should be oppressed by his extraordi
                        <lb break="no"/>nary wrath, but to <choice><orig>thinke</orig> upon escape, if at any time <choice><orig>hee</orig> fall
                        <lb/>into fury without cause, for <choice><orig>hee</orig> when <choice><orig>hee</orig> stops her flying<pc>-</pc>
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="55"/><fw>Discourse 16.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb/>is incited with greater love toward her, <choice><orig>freindship</orig> being made after discord.<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>But you will say who ever saw a <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> with wings, or what can the plumes
                        <lb/>of a <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig> <choice><orig>avayle</orig>? There is a deep valley near the <choice><orig>mountaine</orig> <choice><orig>Cythæren</orig><reg>Cytheran</reg></choice>,
                        <lb/>in which are seen none but flying <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig>, and at the top of the same<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>mountaine</orig> resorts a red <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> of that kind, which Hercules killed. The<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>Lyon</orig> therefore must be taken, and brought into the valley, and forthwith
                        <lb/>coupled to the winged <choice><orig>Lionesse</orig>: <choice><orig>Shee</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> will easily suffer <choice><orig>herselfe</orig> to
                        <lb/>be overcome, as like by like: afterwards they must be both advanced
                        <lb/>out of the <choice><orig>sayd</orig> valley to the top of the <choice><orig>mountaine</orig>, and henceforth they
                        <lb/>will never desert one another, but <choice><orig>allwayes</orig> <choice><orig>remaine</orig> together in inviolable
                        <lb/>amity: The taking of <choice><orig>Lyons</orig>. I <choice><orig>confesse</orig><reg>confess</reg></choice>, is not easy, but obnoxious to many<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>dangers, <choice><orig>neverthelesse</orig> it must be attempted: a <choice><orig>Lyon</orig> feeds not with the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>Lionesse</orig>, but <choice><orig>strayes</orig><reg>strays</reg></choice> apart, as story relates, therefore they are to be found and
                        <lb/>hunted severally: But if the <choice><orig>Lyons</orig> whelps be <choice><orig>obtaind</orig> in their infancy, when
                        <lb/>they first begin to <choice><orig>goe</orig>, which is at two <choice><orig>moneths</orig> age, and be <choice><orig>joyned</orig>, as <choice><orig>afore
                        <lb break="no"/>sayd</orig>, being come to good growth and stature, the thing will be free from<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>any danger. Moreover <seg rend="underline">they breed in the Spring time, which must be well
                        <lb/>observed:</seg> but <choice><orig>Lyons</orig> after whelping using <choice><orig>crosse</orig> and winding <choice><orig>wayes</orig>, to
                        <lb/><orig>prævent</orig> the discovery of their <choice><orig>denne</orig><reg>den</reg></choice>, therefore must they be sought and
                        <lb/>their whelps taken away very great diligence and care<pc>. . . .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
